that we have taken to include R in our electronic submission package.

00:23:36.839 --> 00:23:42.839
As a part of our CDISC submission, we have ensured that the data contents and the formats

00:23:42.839 --> 00:23:50.680
are consistent with the CDISC requirements as an industry-wide standards. The submitted datasets,

00:23:50.680 --> 00:23:58.520
they are all in XPT format, just that they are generated through R. So if we compare with the

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:05.319
traditional package, we can see that the ICTM part remains the same. Just the dataset, they

00:24:05.319 --> 00:24:13.479
were generated from ROAC. Then for the analysis dataset package, the ADAMS dataset also generated

00:24:13.479 --> 00:24:21.079
into XPT format, but written from Admiral Roche, which is currently a proprietary package.

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:28.040
So in this way, the readable code for the ADAMS dataset will be written in Admiral Roche,

00:24:28.599 --> 00:24:35.239
but the readable code for the outputs, like the tables, listings, or graphs, is based on the

00:24:35.239 --> 00:24:42.119
open-source package of turn, so that the end users can easily install and replicate our results.

00:24:43.079 --> 00:24:51.000
Then for the only difference, for the actual efforts, one is to further specify the details

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:57.160
of the R package that have been used in our analysis. And we included this part of the

00:24:57.160 --> 00:25:03.400
content in the document, which we name as Program TOC, in addition to the reviewer's guide.

00:25:04.199 --> 00:25:10.280
The other one is to include the validation reports for the key package that were used in

00:25:10.680 --> 00:25:16.040
our analysis as the miscellaneous datasets to meet the requirements from FDA.

00:25:17.319 --> 00:25:24.119
And then regarding to the validation reports, they are from our internal validation process,

00:25:24.119 --> 00:25:28.839
which has been highly automated. And the recording for the presentation has been

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:34.680
available online, so if you're interested, please feel free to watch.

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:41.880
Now, let's take a look at how we construct the document of the Program TOC to include

00:25:41.880 --> 00:25:47.719
the R information as a disclosure. So as a structure shown on the slide,

00:25:48.760 --> 00:25:55.160
the description of the ESA package provides the general information about our study and

00:25:55.160 --> 00:26:01.959
about our ESA package. Then the list of the analysis dataset programs and the outputs

00:26:01.959 --> 00:26:09.640
programs lists the names of the variables for the datasets for analysis. So far, it mirrors

00:26:09.640 --> 00:26:16.199
what is typically found in the traditional submission, ensuring the consistency and the

00:26:16.199 --> 00:26:23.719
clarity. The final section for how to use the readable code is a place where we provide the

00:26:23.719 --> 00:26:29.640
information about the R package that will have been used in our analysis. And we can see the

00:26:29.640 --> 00:26:38.520
example from the next slide. Yeah, so based on the dynamic nature of R that the advanced feature

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:45.719
are updated to the package with the versioning up. So we also included the version for the package

00:26:45.719 --> 00:26:51.719
along with the very brief description for the package that we used in the analysis.

00:26:51.719 --> 00:26:58.839
So for example, in the proprietary package part, we listed the Miro-Roche since we used it

00:26:58.839 --> 00:27:06.040
for generating our analysis dataset. We also used quite a few open source packages like

00:27:06.040 --> 00:27:13.319
Miro and Tern and also we included the package version and a very brief description

00:27:13.319 --> 00:27:20.040
which can be also taken as the justification of the use. Then in the appendix,

00:27:20.920 --> 00:27:28.280
a very detailed instruction helps the reviewers to install the R environment and the package

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:36.119
along with the example of executing our submitted readable code. This is definitely an optional part

00:27:36.119 --> 00:27:43.319
for the day-to-day R users, but to make our package to be more adaptable for the browser reviewers,

00:27:44.280 --> 00:27:48.920
we still decided to include this part into our submission document.

