work on inviting the generative AI to our code generation in clinical trial reporting.

00:35:13.159 --> 00:35:21.800
And I also want to spend some time to share some reflections from myself to cover the journey

00:35:21.800 --> 00:35:28.360
during the last five years or so. So I remember that the first time I got exposure to our code

00:35:28.360 --> 00:35:35.320
submission to FDA was in 2020. At that time, Roche had a post-marketing commitment to FDA,

00:35:35.320 --> 00:35:41.959
where we needed to do some analysis on a large volume of clinical trial data.

00:35:42.600 --> 00:35:49.000
At that time, for majority of the analysis, we had been using SAS. But there was one particular

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:56.199
set of analysis we needed to use a pretty advanced methodology, in which case it was

00:35:56.199 --> 00:36:01.879
hard to implement using SAS. But there were already existing R code from academia that we

00:36:01.879 --> 00:36:08.520
can directly borrow. So we decided to use the R code to fulfill this post-marketing requirement,

00:36:09.159 --> 00:36:15.479
and then to submit R code to FDA. And at that time, since we didn't have much experience of

00:36:15.479 --> 00:36:19.879
our base submission, there were so many questions internally. For example,

00:36:19.879 --> 00:36:25.560
our biggest question is around how can we make sure the FDA reviewers will be able to reproduce

00:36:25.560 --> 00:36:31.639
the results, how to ensure that they can work in a similar computing environment as we do.

00:36:32.199 --> 00:36:38.199
For example, two very simple questions are like how do we share the open source packages we use

